.TH PROGPATH 3 "" "progpath" "Library Functions Manual"
.SH NAME
progpath, progipwd \- get an executable path and initial working directory
.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
.B #define PROGPATH_IMPLEMENTATION
.br
.B #include <progpath.h>
.PP
.BI "char *progpath(char *" buf ", size_t " len );
.BI "char *progipwd(char *" buf ", size_t " len );
.fi
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B progpath()
returns the path to the running program's executable image.
.PP
.B progipwd()
returns the process working directory as it was when the program started,
so it remains available even after later calls to
.BR chdir (2).
.PP
If
.I buf
is not
.BR NULL ,
the result is written into the caller-supplied buffer and the return value is
.IR buf .
At most
.I len \- 1
bytes are written so the result remains NUL-terminated.
.PP
If
.I buf
is
.BR NULL ,
memory is allocated with
.BR calloc (3)
and the caller must release it with
.BR free (3).
.SH INITIALIZATION
.B progpath
captures the initial working directory once, as early as possible.
How that happens depends on how progpath is integrated:
.TP
Single-header implementation compiled as C++
Initialization happens automatically before
.BR main .
.TP
Single-header implementation compiled as C
Initialization is lazy.
Call
.B progipwd()
or
.B progpath()
early in
.BR main ,
before any explicit
.B chdir()
call.
The implementation emits a compile-time warning in this mode unless
.B PROGPATH_NO_C_INIT_WARNING
is defined.
.TP
Shared library
Initialization happens automatically before
.BR main .
.TP
Static library linked from C++
Initialization also happens automatically before
.BR main .
.TP
Static library linked from pure C
Initialization is lazy.
Call
.B progipwd()
or
.B progpath()
early in
.BR main ,
before any explicit
.B chdir()
call.
.SH RETURN VALUE
On success,
.B progpath()
and
.B progipwd()
return a pointer to the resulting string.
This is either the caller-provided buffer or a dynamically allocated buffer.
On failure,
.B NULL
is returned.
.SH THREAD SAFETY
Do not call
.B progpath()
or
.B progipwd()
concurrently before the initial capture has completed.
Initialize from the main thread before creating additional threads.
.PP
Some lookup methods may temporarily restore the initial working directory while
resolving a full executable path.
Treat the API as not thread-safe with respect to concurrent directory changes.
.SH EXAMPLE
.nf
char pp[4096];
progpath(pp, sizeof(pp));

char *ipwd;
ipwd = progipwd(NULL, 0);
free(ipwd);
.fi
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR chdir (2),
.BR getcwd (3),
.BR realpath (3),
.BR free (3)
